Water bowser seen in Karen, Nairobi. [James Mwangi, Standard]  Residents of various Nairobi estates will have to stock up enough water for a day, to avoid shortage and inconveniences.  This follows a directive by the Nairobi City Water and Sewerage Company (NCWSC) to shut down the water supply pipeline along Uhuru Highway due to ongoing construction of the Nairobi Express Way, from Thursday, July 15 at 6.00 am to Friday 6.00 am.  “This will facilitate interconnection of the relocated new and old water pipelines on Uhuru Highway between Haile Selassie Avenue and Bunyala Road junctions with Uhuru Highway to enable the release of the road corridor to the Expressway Road Contractor,” the water company said in a statement on Wednesday.  The affected areas include; The city centre, areas along Mombasa Road, South B and C and its environs and the University of Nairobi city campus.  Group collects waste in Nairobi estates, streets  Environmentalists push drive on waste collection in Nairobi estates  Nairobi’s thirsty slums enjoy free water for the first time  Nairobi taps to go dry for next two days Others are Coca Cola Factory, JKIA, EPZ-Athi River, Industrial Area, areas along Jogoo Road- City Stadium, Maringo, Bahati, Buru Buru and their surrounding estates.  Residents have been urged to use water sparingly to avert a crisis situation until services resume normalcy.   Water Boost: World bank gives a grant of Ksh 32 million to boost water supply to Murang'a residents  Nairobi's dry taps: Nairobi residents have no water supply from sasumwa dam shut down  78 people in Madogo - Tana River County admitted after an outbreak of cholera in the region By Kamore Maina | 8 hours ago By Kamau Muthoni | 12 hours ago By Kamau Muthoni | 13 hours ago By Kamore Maina | 17 hours ago